description: Migraine with aura is a type of migraine headache that is preceded by an aura. An aura is a temporary change in brain function that can cause a variety of symptoms, such as visual disturbances, tingling sensations, or difficulty speaking. Migraines with aura are often very painful and can last for several hours or even days. The exact cause of migraines is unknown, but they are thought to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors.

description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain. TIAs are sometimes called ministrokes. TIAs cause symptoms similar to those of a stroke, but the symptoms usually last for only a few minutes. TIAs are a serious medical condition because they can be a warning sign of a future stroke. The risk of stroke is highest in the weeks following a TIA.
prevalence: 500,000 cases per year in the US

description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic disease that affects the central nervous system. MS damages the myelin sheath, which is the protective covering that surrounds nerve fibers. This damage disrupts the transmission of nerve signals, which can cause a wide range of symptoms, including weakness, numbness, tingling, and vision problems. MS is most commonly diagnosed in young adults, and it affects women more often than men.

description: A stroke is a serious medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to the brain is interrupted. This can happen when a blood clot blocks an artery in the brain, or when a blood vessel in the brain ruptures. When blood flow is interrupted, the brain cells are deprived of oxygen and nutrients, which can lead to cell death. Strokes can cause a wide range of symptoms, depending on the part of the brain that is affected. Common symptoms include weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, and vision problems.
prevalence: 870,000 cases per year in the US

description: Bells palsy is a temporary paralysis of the facial muscles. It is caused by damage to the facial nerve, which controls the muscles that make facial expressions. Bells palsy usually affects only one side of the face, and it can cause weakness, drooping, and numbness in the affected muscles. Bells palsy is usually not serious, and most people recover completely within a few weeks or months.
prevalence: 40,000 cases per year in the US

description: Lyme disease is a bacterial infection that is spread by ticks. Lyme disease can cause a wide range of symptoms, including fever, chills, headache, fatigue, and muscle aches. In some cases, Lyme disease can also cause weakness, numbness, and tingling. Lyme disease is treated with antibiotics.
prevalence: 300,000 cases per year in the US

description: Guillain-Barré syndrome is a rare disorder that affects the nerves. It can cause weakness, numbness, and tingling in the arms and legs. In some cases, it can also cause paralysis. Guillain-Barré syndrome is thought to be an autoimmune disorder, which means that the bodys immune system attacks its own nerves. Guillain-Barré syndrome can be treated with plasma exchange or intravenous immunoglobulin therapy.
prevalence: 1 case per 100,000 people per year

description: Vitamin B12 deficiency is a deficiency of vitamin B12, which is an essential nutrient that is needed for the production of red blood cells and for healthy nerve function. Vitamin B12 deficiency can cause a wide range of symptoms, including weakness, numbness, and tingling. It can also cause anemia and fatigue. Vitamin B12 deficiency is treated with vitamin B12 supplements.

description: Cervical radiculopathy is a condition that occurs when a nerve in the neck is compressed. This can cause pain, numbness, and weakness in the arm or hand. Cervical radiculopathy is most commonly caused by arthritis or a herniated disc.
prevalence: 85 cases per 100,000 people per year

description: Carpal tunnel syndrome is a condition that occurs when the median nerve is compressed in the wrist. This can cause pain, numbness, and tingling in the hand and fingers. Carpal tunnel syndrome is most commonly caused by repetitive hand movements.

treatment: The treatment for carpal tunnel syndrome depends on the severity of the condition. Mild cases may be treated with wrist splints or corticosteroid injections. More severe cases may require surgery.
